.Dd $Mdocdate$
.Dt TMPL_NEW 3
.Os
.Sh NAME
.Nm tmpl_new ,
.Nm tmpl_ref ,
.Nm tmpl_unref ,
.Nm tmpl_unrefp
.Nd allocate and manage the lifetime of template objects
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.In tmpl/tmpl.h
.Ft int
.Fn tmpl_new "struct tmpl **ret"
.Ft "struct tmpl *"
.Fn tmpl_ref "struct tmpl *t"
.Ft "struct tmpl *"
.Fn tmpl_unref "struct tmpl *t"
.Ft void
.Fn tmpl_unrefp "struct tmpl **t"
.Sh DESCRIPTION
The
.Fn tmpl_new
function allocates a new
.Vt tmpl
object with a reference count of one and stores a pointer to it in
.Fa *ret .
.Pp
.Fn tmpl_ref
increments the reference count of
.Fa t
and returns
.Fa t .
If
.Fa t
is
.Dv NULL ,
it returns
.Dv NULL
and takes no action.
.Pp
.Fn tmpl_unref
decrements the reference count of
.Fa t .
When the count reaches zero the object is freed.
Returns
.Dv NULL
in all cases.
If
.Fa t
is
.Dv NULL ,
no action is taken.
.Pp
.Fn tmpl_unrefp
calls
.Fn tmpl_unref
on
.Fa *t
and sets
.Fa *t
to
.Dv NULL .
It is intended for use with the
.Dv _cleanup_tmpl_
attribute, which arranges for automatic release when a variable goes out
of scope:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
_cleanup_tmpl_ struct tmpl *t = NULL;
int r;

r = tmpl_new(&t);
if(r < 0){
        errno = -r;
        err(1, "tmpl_new");
}
/* t is released automatically on all exit paths */
.Ed
.Sh RETURN VALUES
.Fn tmpl_new
returns 0 on success or a negative
.Xr errno 2
value on failure.
.Fn tmpl_ref
returns its argument.
.Fn tmpl_unref
always returns
.Dv NULL .
.Sh ERRORS
.Bl -tag -width Er
.It Bq Er ENOMEM
.Fn tmpl_new
failed to allocate memory.
.El
.Sh SEE ALSO
.Xr tmpl_parse 3
